Hassan Ugael is a professor of visual computing

26
00:01:06,319 --> 00:01:07,920
at the University of Bradford.

27
00:01:07,920 --> 00:01:09,920
He's been working on getting computers

28
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:12,479
to be able to recognise human emotions

29
00:01:12,479 --> 00:01:14,399
from the expressions on our face.

30
00:01:15,120 --> 00:01:19,120
Here he is speaking on the BBC Inside Science Radio programme.

31
00:01:19,120 --> 00:01:21,920
How successful does he say they have been?

32
00:01:21,920 --> 00:01:24,640
We've been working quite a lot on the human emotions

33
00:01:24,640 --> 00:01:28,239
or the ideas how the facial muscle movement

34
00:01:28,319 --> 00:01:30,319
which is reflected on the face,

35
00:01:30,319 --> 00:01:33,039
through obviously computer, through video frames,

36
00:01:33,039 --> 00:01:35,280
and trying to understand how these muscle movements

37
00:01:35,280 --> 00:01:38,000
actually relate to facial expressions

38
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:39,599
and then from facial expressions,

39
00:01:39,599 --> 00:01:43,199
trying to understand the emotions or to infer the emotions.

40
00:01:43,199 --> 00:01:45,359
And we have been quite successful in doing that.

41
00:01:45,359 --> 00:01:48,879
We have software that can actually look at somebody's face

42
00:01:48,879 --> 00:01:53,439
in real time and then identify the series of emotions

43
00:01:53,439 --> 00:01:56,479
that persons express in real time as well.

44
00:01:56,560 --> 00:01:59,520
So, have they been successful in getting computers

45
00:01:59,520 --> 00:02:01,359
to identify emotions?

46
00:02:01,359 --> 00:02:04,159
Yes, he says they've been quite successful.

47
00:02:04,159 --> 00:02:06,159
And what's interesting is that he says

48
00:02:06,159 --> 00:02:09,920
that the computers can do it in real time.

49
00:02:09,920 --> 00:02:12,480
This means that there's no delay.

50
00:02:12,480 --> 00:02:15,039
They don't have to stop and analyse the data

51
00:02:15,039 --> 00:02:16,400
or crunch the numbers.

52
00:02:16,400 --> 00:02:19,360
They can do it as the person is talking.

53
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:23,040
The system uses video to analyse a person's expressions

54
00:02:23,040 --> 00:02:25,439
and can then infer the emotions.

55
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:28,400
To infer something means to get an understanding of something

56
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:31,039
without actually being told directly.

57
00:02:31,039 --> 00:02:32,879
So, you look at available information

58
00:02:32,879 --> 00:02:34,879
and use your understanding and knowledge

59
00:02:34,879 --> 00:02:36,560
to work out the meaning.

60
00:02:36,560 --> 00:02:39,039
It's a bit like being a detective, isn't it?

61
00:02:39,039 --> 00:02:42,079
You look at the clues and infer what happened

62
00:02:42,079 --> 00:02:44,240
even if you don't have all the details.

63
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:46,400
Yes, and in this case, the computer looks

64
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:48,560
at how the movement of muscles in the face

65
00:02:48,560 --> 00:02:51,599
or facial muscles show different emotions.

66
