80
00:03:27,919 --> 00:03:32,959
So, how do the computers know what is a real or a fake smile?

81
00:03:32,959 --> 00:03:34,799
The computers have to learn that first.

82
00:03:35,759 --> 00:03:39,599
Here's Professor Ugeh again talking about how they do that.

83
00:03:39,599 --> 00:03:41,839
We have a data set of real smiles

84
00:03:41,839 --> 00:03:43,839
and we have a data set of fake smiles.

85
00:03:43,839 --> 00:03:46,159
These real smiles are indeed smiles in a lab.

86
00:03:46,159 --> 00:03:48,000
So, you put somebody on the chair

87
00:03:48,080 --> 00:03:50,560
and then show some funny movies

88
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:53,280
and we expect the smiles are genuine smiles.

89
00:03:53,280 --> 00:03:56,240
And similarly, we ask them to pretend they're smile

90
00:03:56,240 --> 00:03:58,159
so these are what we call fake smiles.

91
00:03:58,159 --> 00:04:01,439
So, what we do is we throw these into the machine

92
00:04:01,439 --> 00:04:03,199
and then the machine figures out

93
00:04:03,199 --> 00:04:05,680
what are the characteristics of a real smile

94
00:04:05,680 --> 00:04:07,920
and what are the characteristics of a fake smile.

95
00:04:08,639 --> 00:04:11,759
So, how do they get the data that the computers use

96
00:04:11,759 --> 00:04:14,400
to see if your smile is fake or genuine,

97
00:04:14,400 --> 00:04:16,160
which is another word which means real?

98
00:04:16,800 --> 00:04:19,520
They induce real smiles in the lab

99
00:04:19,520 --> 00:04:21,520
